It must not be assumed that the work of Minucius is merely the product of these various influences and that the clement of originality is lacking. Individuality, on the contrary, was a feature of all the African writers.¹ Minucius is a stylist‚ a conscious artist who appreciated the value of form while rejecting the false canons of Fronto. He tempers symmetry with variety, oratorical fulness with brevity and concision. The result is a style of writing fresh, picturesque, rich, harmonicus and complex.
